00:08:33.100 --> 00:08:35.840
and I did finally make it to
Rare Books and Manuscripts,

00:08:35.840 --> 00:08:38.940
so thanks to Michael North, Maphon
Ashman, Stephanie and others

00:08:38.940 --> 00:08:44.370
who helped me track down the books
I needed including this book,

00:08:44.370 --> 00:08:46.340
Ann Mary Dutton's book from 1800.

00:08:46.340 --> 00:08:50.560
In 18th Century and 19th
Century English language sources,

00:08:50.560 --> 00:08:53.130
they make clear distinctions
between the words "to preserve,"

00:08:53.130 --> 00:08:54.690
which means to use sugar, right?

00:08:54.690 --> 00:08:57.540
"To pickle," which means to
use a salt brine or vinegar.

00:08:57.540 --> 00:09:01.200
And "to keep," which means to
maintain for a relatively long time

00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:05.790
and relative means like
until Christmas or all winter

00:09:05.790 --> 00:09:10.190
or the next year without the use
of a taste-altering preservative.

00:09:10.190 --> 00:09:15.630
So that distinction and we often
think about as being just part

00:09:15.630 --> 00:09:18.560
of contemporary canning where you
don't add sugar and things, right?

00:09:18.560 --> 00:09:22.450
You can find it in these
older books as well.

00:09:22.450 --> 00:09:26.990
This so called "cold water method"
to keep barberries that's up here,

00:09:26.990 --> 00:09:30.350
that was still being advocated
in 1919 to preserve rhubarb,

00:09:30.350 --> 00:09:35.130
cranberries, gooseberries and sour
cherries although the 1919 author,

00:09:35.130 --> 00:09:37.940
Olive Hayes, noted in italics that,

00:09:37.940 --> 00:09:40.590
"this method is not
always successful

00:09:40.590 --> 00:09:43.530
as the acid content varies with
the ripeness and the locality

00:09:43.530 --> 00:09:45.040
in which the fruits are grown."

00:09:45.040 --> 00:09:49.550
I'll come back to her concern
with context a little bit later.

00:09:49.550 --> 00:09:54.960
Also in Rare Books, I found this
British bill-of-fare published

00:09:54.960 --> 00:09:58.740 position:56%
in 1708 which called for February
meals that included peas, asparagus,

00:09:58.740 --> 00:10:01.200
strawberries and cream,
several apple pies,

00:10:01.200 --> 00:10:03.440
raspberry cream and
gooseberry tarts.

00:10:03.440 --> 00:10:06.190
Some of the fruit had probably
been over-wintered in cool cellars

00:10:06.190 --> 00:10:07.780
or forced early in greenhouses.

00:10:07.780 --> 00:10:11.040
The menus were created
by Henry Howard,

00:10:11.040 --> 00:10:12.530
who was a well-regarded
chef employed

00:10:12.530 --> 00:10:14.170
by several members of aristocracy.

00:10:14.170 --> 00:10:16.590
So he would have had
access to hot houses,

00:10:16.590 --> 00:10:18.640
but the gooseberry tarts were
possible because at least

00:10:18.640 --> 00:10:23.080
by the late 1680s people knew
how to store firm, whole, firm,

00:10:23.080 --> 00:10:26.110
acidic fruits including
gooseberries, currants, cherries,

00:10:26.110 --> 00:10:29.820
bases and damsons in
sealed bottles and jars.

00:10:29.820 --> 00:10:33.050
And basses and damsons like
plums belong to the genus prunus

00:10:33.050 --> 00:10:38.180
but are smaller, drier and tarter
than their sweet, meaty cousins.

00:10:38.180 --> 00:10:42.710
This book, which included the
menus, was first published in 1703.

00:10:42.710 --> 00:10:46.130
By 1726 the book had gone
into a fifth printing.

00:10:46.130 --> 00:10:50.000
A recipe Howard calls "to keep
gooseberries" appeared unchanged

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:53.810
in the second edition and fifth
printing and exactly as it appears

00:10:53.810 --> 00:10:58.040
in the original 1703 book as well.

00:10:58.040 --> 00:11:01.540
As you'll see, the recipe relies on
two, the two procedures fundamental

00:11:01.540 --> 00:11:03.310
to what we now call canning.

00:11:03.310 --> 00:11:06.960
First, existing detrimental yeast,
mold and bacteria are killed

00:11:06.960 --> 00:11:09.550
or retarded through the
application of heat.

00:11:09.550 --> 00:11:11.850
And second, further
contamination is minimized

00:11:11.850 --> 00:11:14.460
by sealing the container,
by stopping [inaudible].

00:11:14.460 --> 00:11:19.350
Notice that he actually calls
for clarified mutton fat

00:11:19.350 --> 00:11:22.160
to be used to seal the damsons.

00:11:22.160 --> 00:11:27.130
And what's interesting, so, in
the preface to this book he talks

00:11:27.130 --> 00:11:28.430
about the different kind

00:11:28.430 --> 00:11:30.550
of manuscript sources
that these come from.

