00:13:00.670 --> 00:13:05.190
over a few food safety
principles that would be useful

00:13:05.190 --> 00:13:07.830
in understanding the rest of
the conversation today, right?

00:13:07.830 --> 00:13:12.200
So, first you need to kill
or disable existing microbes.

00:13:12.200 --> 00:13:14.410
You can do that through
sterilization,

00:13:14.410 --> 00:13:17.190
high temps over sufficient
enough time.

00:13:17.190 --> 00:13:20.730
You can also add sugar
or salt or acid

00:13:20.730 --> 00:13:23.600
or you can dehydrate
things for desiccation.

00:13:23.600 --> 00:13:25.770
Once you have sort of
disabled the microbes,

00:13:25.770 --> 00:13:27.690
you need to keep the
microbes out so you need

00:13:27.690 --> 00:13:29.210
to have some sort of a seal, right?

00:13:29.210 --> 00:13:31.280
So that's sort of the base of
parameters we're working within.

00:13:31.280 --> 00:13:36.820
And you can see that in this
1876 set of instructions

00:13:36.820 --> 00:13:41.640
where you take cold fruit and
put hot syrup and put into a jar

00:13:41.640 --> 00:13:44.860
and place the open jar in a
boiler lined with a grate, pebbles

00:13:44.860 --> 00:13:46.980
and straw to sort of
protect it from breakage.

00:13:46.980 --> 00:13:52.360
You fill it up with water to the
neck, you cover the boiler and boil

00:13:52.360 --> 00:13:56.760
for a specific amount of time
depending on what you're cooking.

00:13:56.760 --> 00:13:59.720
You remove it and let the
jar stand for five minutes

00:13:59.720 --> 00:14:05.540 position:56%
and then you add a rubber ring and a
cap and screw it down with a wrench

00:14:05.540 --> 00:14:10.130
because this is a zinc cap that you
have to really put a lot of effort

00:14:10.130 --> 00:14:14.340 position:56%
in to getting it down there, but you
can see this is a little problematic

00:14:14.340 --> 00:14:17.380
because it doesn't add the seal

00:14:17.380 --> 00:14:19.750
until after the sterilization
has already processed, right?

00:14:19.750 --> 00:14:24.870
So you've got a chance for
contamination to occur.

00:14:24.870 --> 00:14:27.740
So, again, you need to
it in that order, right?

00:14:27.740 --> 00:14:31.540
First you sort of cover
it, you sterilize it,

00:14:31.540 --> 00:14:33.270
and then you make sure
that it's sealed.

00:14:33.270 --> 00:14:34.780
Air tight.

00:14:34.780 --> 00:14:38.700
Okay. So the last acknowledgement I
want to give is to Benjamin Botkin

00:14:38.700 --> 00:14:40.770
for whom this lecture
series is named.

00:14:40.770 --> 00:14:44.120
He is shown here in this Victory
Garden during World War II.

00:14:44.120 --> 00:14:45.420
Botkin championed the notion

00:14:45.420 --> 00:14:48.930
that vernacular expressive culture
is always relevant to contemporary,

00:14:48.930 --> 00:14:50.690
social and political life.

00:14:50.690 --> 00:14:52.550
The pattern of things people say,

00:14:52.550 --> 00:14:57.580
do and make in everyday life are
not merely practical or decorative,

00:14:57.580 --> 00:15:01.180
but in fact, they shape
structures of power.

00:15:01.180 --> 00:15:03.550 position:56%
And home canning is a case in point.

00:15:03.550 --> 00:15:06.440
Shelf stable canned goods have been
a part of everyday American life

00:15:06.440 --> 00:15:08.310
since the mid-19th Century.

00:15:08.310 --> 00:15:12.490 position:56%
Where industrial canning utilized
metal tins and mechanized processes,

00:15:12.490 --> 00:15:15.190
other forms of canning came
to rely on glass bottles

00:15:15.190 --> 00:15:17.320
and the domestic labor of women.

00:15:17.320 --> 00:15:21.090
I should reiterate that in the
United States home canning has come

00:15:21.090 --> 00:15:23.200
to refer almost exclusively
to preserving fruit

00:15:23.200 --> 00:15:27.460
and vegetables in air tight jars.

00:15:27.460 --> 00:15:30.420
In the literature, it's not
unusual to hear people talk

00:15:30.420 --> 00:15:34.280
about glass cans, right, when
they're referring to jars.

00:15:34.280 --> 00:15:37.070
Of course the job has not
fallen exclusively to women.

00:15:37.070 --> 00:15:39.190
So here you see this couple
from New Mexico working

00:15:39.190 --> 00:15:44.040
on currants and apricots.

00:15:44.040 --> 00:15:46.310
That said, the story of
canning is complicated, right?

00:15:46.310 --> 00:15:49.680
Even in the early 1900s the
practice had multiple meanings.

00:15:49.680 --> 00:15:52.710
For some, home canning was
old-fashioned, inefficient

00:15:52.710 --> 00:15:56.800
or embarrassing already
by like the early 1900s.

00:15:56.800 --> 00:15:59.940
For others is a valuable skill
to be displayed in public

00:15:59.940 --> 00:16:02.890
and mobilized in times of need.

00:16:02.890 --> 00:16:06.770
In today's context of economic
instability, automated systems

00:16:06.770 --> 00:16:09.030
and cultural and environmental
change,

00:16:09.030 --> 00:16:12.700
do- it-yourself canning
is experiencing a revival.

00:16:12.700 --> 00:16:15.150
More people are canning
their own food.

00:16:15.150 --> 00:16:18.190
The process can be a way to
recall people and places;

00:16:18.190 --> 00:16:22.320
to confirm authentic or esoteric
taste; and to enact abstract values

00:16:22.320 --> 00:16:25.110
such as stewardship
or self-sufficiency.

00:16:25.110 --> 00:16:28.150
That is a vernacular process
like canning becomes instrumental

00:16:28.150 --> 00:16:31.740
in articulating and further
materializing ideographs:

00:16:31.740 --> 00:16:34.720
Those seemingly self-evident
words and phrases that,

00:16:34.720 --> 00:16:38.490
"function as guides,
warrants, reasons or excuses

00:16:38.490 --> 00:16:39.790
for behavior and belief".

00:16:39.790 --> 00:16:41.590
And that's Michael McGee.

00:16:41.590 --> 00:16:47.020
These one term sums of an
orientation include things

00:16:47.020 --> 00:16:52.060
like tradition, heritage,
authenticity, art, identity,

00:16:52.060 --> 00:16:54.410
but also a number of
key words and code words

00:16:54.410 --> 00:16:57.800
that index broader cultural
narratives and ideologies.

00:16:57.800 --> 00:16:59.720
I'll show you a few examples.

00:16:59.720 --> 00:17:04.430
So, one cultural narrative
or sort of ideograph

00:17:04.430 --> 00:17:08.190
that indexes these larger
cultural narratives is creativity.

00:17:08.190 --> 00:17:12.940
These images, one from 2011
and the other from the 1940s,

00:17:12.940 --> 00:17:15.730
demonstrate how canning can be
an expressive creative practice;

00:17:15.730 --> 00:17:17.560
not merely a practical one.

00:17:17.560 --> 00:17:21.030
People often think of canning in
the past as people just did it

00:17:21.030 --> 00:17:23.770
because they had to but we do
it now because we choose to,

00:17:23.770 --> 00:17:29.210 position:56%
but that's not an accurate depiction
of what, from what I have found

00:17:29.210 --> 00:17:30.930 position:56%
of people's motivations for canning.

00:17:30.930 --> 00:17:33.980
Beauty has always been something

00:17:33.980 --> 00:17:36.500
that people have been
interested in and sought after.

00:17:36.500 --> 00:17:40.710
I'm going to show you a
range of photos that sort

00:17:40.710 --> 00:17:43.520
of emphasize how home canning
can be a sign of display.

00:17:43.520 --> 00:17:48.320
So here you have Mrs. Frank Jacobs,
who is carefully placing pears

00:17:48.320 --> 00:17:51.700
in a jar and that has a
practical effect of making sure

00:17:51.700 --> 00:17:53.710
that you got it closed
in efficient pack, right?

00:17:53.710 --> 00:17:56.880
It seems to be floating up.

00:17:56.880 --> 00:18:02.460 position:56%
But it's also aesthetically pleasing
especially in terms of evenness

00:18:02.460 --> 00:18:08.850
and regularity, which is often
valued by people who can.

00:18:08.850 --> 00:18:14.300
Here's another sort of
sense of canning as display.

00:18:14.300 --> 00:18:20.190
You can't see the sign very well
right here, but it's actually sort

00:18:20.190 --> 00:18:22.410
of a call for people
to contribute exhibits,

00:18:22.410 --> 00:18:24.860
sort of a rotating exhibit.

00:18:24.860 --> 00:18:28.370
Each of these has the name
of the woman who made it.

00:18:28.370 --> 00:18:32.980
Some of them I have been able
to read with magnification,

00:18:32.980 --> 00:18:36.930
but this display is
interesting in that it sort

00:18:36.930 --> 00:18:39.190
of brings together
national security--

00:18:39.190 --> 00:18:41.400
which I'll get to in a
moment because it's part

00:18:41.400 --> 00:18:45.240
of a World War I era display--

00:18:45.240 --> 00:18:48.550
but it's also a chance in
this public venue, right,

00:18:48.550 --> 00:18:53.510
the Library for women to
display their handiwork.

00:18:53.510 --> 00:18:58.030
And here we have the
Gonzales County Fair.

00:18:58.030 --> 00:19:02.630
I should say that display is not
incidental among many canners.

00:19:02.630 --> 00:19:07.270
It may actually affect the
procedures that they employ.

00:19:07.270 --> 00:19:11.280
One Illinois bacteriologist noted
in 1935 that taste, texture,

00:19:11.280 --> 00:19:14.240
color and arrangement of jarred
foods are one thing when it comes

00:19:14.240 --> 00:19:16.670
to earning social recognition
at the county fair,

00:19:16.670 --> 00:19:19.630 position:56%
but concern about public health
risks should trump other performance

00:19:19.630 --> 00:19:21.050
agendas, he thought.

00:19:21.050 --> 00:19:23.940
He railed against housewives
and their ill-informed teachers

00:19:23.940 --> 00:19:26.540
who use unsafe procedures
in the name of display.

00:19:26.540 --> 00:19:29.820
Numerous books, he observed,
caution that "temperatures higher

00:19:29.820 --> 00:19:32.590
than boiling tend to
injure the delicate color

00:19:32.590 --> 00:19:34.760
and texture of most fruits".

00:19:34.760 --> 00:19:38.160
In an attempt to preserve flavor
and yet address growing awareness

00:19:38.160 --> 00:19:42.030 position:56%
of microscopic threats, in the early
1900s some canners experimented

00:19:42.030 --> 00:19:46.580
with sterilization process in
which food was heated several times

00:19:46.580 --> 00:19:49.000
but at temperatures below boiling.

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:55.780
And this is also a similar process
was actually promoted by the USDA

00:19:55.780 --> 00:20:00.770
in the teens: the intermittent
method

00:20:00.770 --> 00:20:05.390
as a way to sort of kill off...

00:20:05.390 --> 00:20:09.810
The idea was that spores might
not germinate the first day

00:20:09.810 --> 00:20:11.500
but if you waited another
day then they would germinate

00:20:11.500 --> 00:20:13.370
and then you could boil them
again and kill that, right?

00:20:13.370 --> 00:20:20.080
In 1932, well, actually in 1913,
three students at Stanford died

00:20:20.080 --> 00:20:23.870
because they ate food
using this method.

00:20:23.870 --> 00:20:28.230
So it does have some risks.

00:20:29.340 --> 00:20:35.760
Here's another sort of version
of canning as a site for display.

00:20:35.760 --> 00:20:40.050
This is from the 1960s and
